    {
      "id": "commentary",
      "html": "<h2>commentary</h2>  <p>The text is speculatively restored in several different ways by previous editors: the text of Manganaro 1977 is provided here as an example; Gentili 1961 instead suggested a dedication to Demeter and Kore by Gelon, son of Hieron. Manganaro is correct that there is theoretically space for a shorter fourth line, and the dedication to Zeus Hellanios in honour of Gelon (<a href=\"http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic003331\" target=\"_blank\">ISic003331</a> provides a plausible parallel.</p>  "
    },
    {
      "id": "bibliography",
      "html": "<h2>bibliography</h2>  <ul><li> 56.1103.2.2 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796</a>  </li><li> 34.0979 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796</a>  </li><li> Gentili 1959-1960 19-20 fig.2 </li><li> Gentili 1961 8-10 no.3 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001955\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001955</a>  </li><li> Manganaro 1963 24 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001848\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001848</a>  </li><li> Manganaro 1965 186 no.2 tav.64 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001841\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001841</a>  </li><li> Manganaro 1965 315 n.11 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001840\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001840</a>  </li><li> Manganaro 1977 155-156 dr ph </li><li> Dimartino 2006 no.2.2 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002022\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002022</a>  </li></ul>  <ul><li></li></ul>  "
    },
    {
      "id": "handnote",
      "html": " <p>Thinly incised broad letters of regular height, without serifs or marked terminations to the strokes. Alpha has straight bar; Beta has closed loops, in the second instance separated from one another. Sigma has parallel top and bottom strokes, the mid-strokes meeting slightly over halfway across.</p> <p> Types list: <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Α-type1.html\" target=\"_blank\">Α type1</a> <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Α-type1.3.html\" target=\"_blank\">Α type1.3</a> <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Β-type2.html\" target=\"_blank\">Β type2</a> <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Β-type2.1.html\" target=\"_blank\">Β type2.1</a> <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Ι-type1.html\" target=\"_blank\">Ι type1</a> <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Σ-tyoe3.2.html\" target=\"_blank\">Σ tyoe3.2</a> <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Σ-type3.html\" target=\"_blank\">Σ type3</a> </p> Line 1-3  60  Interlineation line 1 to 2  not measured  "
